title: For Sale:  Phil Spangenburger SAA 45 Colt Cased Texas
postcontent: Phil Spangenburger cased set made in 1987 for the Texas Gunslingers. Its a cased single gun made by Uberti but not marked with any Italian names or even proof marks, it has them marked under the ejector rod housing. It has "Shootist Edition" Engraved on top of the 4 3/4's inch barrel, its marked 1 of 1,000 on the left side of the frame, and its engraved Phil Spangenberger on the back strap. Its got beautiful Nickle finish on the metal and the grips are nice looking 1 piece wood, correct for a black powder frame era gun which this is a replica of. It has the correct "Bullseye" ejector rod and of course the screw retainer for the cylinder base pin.In the presentation case are 33-45 Colt caliber cartridges, made by Winchester and an antique looking picture of Phil holding one of these guns, its autographed and dated 1987. There is also a poker card that's been shot 3 times and its autographed by Phil as well and dated 6/15/1987. Phil told me there was supposed to be 1000 sets of the single gun made up but the guy in charge had his wife pass away from cancer at the time of this and was so distraught that they quit the project. Phil also talked of sets with 2 guns that were engraved and with genuine pearl grips,he has a set of those, he stated they were beautiful, numbered 2 & 3 I think, sounds like quite a set, these engraved sets were originally slated for 100 sets to be made but they probably only made 20 or so. Mine is a cased single gun from the standard non engraved series and its serial numbered PS0039, so the 39th gun made, the compartment-ed case is what looks like oak wood with green billiard cloth lining. On top of the case is one of Phils favorite saying engraved on a brass plaque that states "Always be sure to aim, and always aim to be sure" gotta like all of this, a quality package to be sure. This gun is in excellent to new condition and the case is excellent plus. The picture and card are excellent and there is also a gold seal with the name of "Texas Gunfighters" and the date of 1987. Phil was very kind and sent me a copy of the article in Guns & Ammo magazine from 1988 and I have added a copy of that with this set. Phil's partner in the "Texas Gunslingers was also very kind and sent me a nice letter that I will include a copy of too. If interested I will send a letter from me stating all of this. I think this will all be a collectors item someday, as far as i'm concerned it's a collectors item right now and I'm OK to keep it,but I will sell it as I'm in the business of selling guns more than in the collectors business, some times you have to make that choice,

Many years ago when we began selling our knives to the Military, our salesmanager at the time felt that soldiers would not be interested in a knife called a "Ladybug". So we called in a "Little Big Knife" (LBK) with special packaging.sal... ".   I've conversed with many of the long time Spyderco expert/collectors and none had ever seen one before.  I have 3 of them that were NOS at a local gun/pawn shop.  They spent over 20 years being shuffled from hooks to display cases but nobody in my town was willing to pay the high even at today's standards 1990 msrp for a tiny little knife they never heard of in an ugly plastic blister pack.  I'm told it was a very lucky find as they are worth 10x what I paid. Only minus is the plastic is old faded and cracking due to age etc. I'm keeping at least one for my collection, but you can have your choice of the other two or both... depending on what you have to trade.  I'm not sure of the value but I have a general idea and am open to reasonable offers.  I also have a C133 set.. you can still get the knives seperatly for around $60 or so, but the set was discontinued last year so it's worth more than the individual knives now(obviously) and an instant collectible. Lastly is a Delica 1 thin clip in G2 steel.  I believe it's the first version made in 1990. later Gen 1s had a thicker clip, and were made of AUS8.  It is used, with no box, but is in excellent condition and is razor sharp.  I hand tied a Sebenza style paracord  lanyard on it because I carry it occasionally and don't use the clip for fear of bending or breaking it.besides the knives I have .22 lr ammo in a plethora of varieties, and a Simmons 8-32 X 44 scope.What do you got? what do you want for it?
